% Hook
According to most political economists, fiscal sociologists, development economist and economic historians, fiscal capacities are a prerequisite for state-building. Unfortunately, there have not been many attempts to explain \emph{why} and \emph{how} state and fiscal capacities in the developing world emerged.\footnote{\citet[5]{DiJohn2006}.} With a few exceptions, most efforts have been devoted to understanding the relationship between the politics of taxation and state capacities only in a limited number of European cases. In a recently edited volume, \citet[3]{Monson2015} explain that the ``New Fiscal History has furnished a valuable set of concepts and questions but so far its scope has been limited to post-classical Europe.''\footnote{Some important exceptions are \citet{Yun-Casalilla:2015zm} and \citet[]{Monson2015} who study a number of premodern states.} In fact, the bulk of research on Latin America has mostly focused on \emph{recent} tax reforms.\footnote{\citet[]{Fairfield2013} studies different strategies policymakers pursue to tax elites starting in 1990. \citet[]{Mahon2004} and \citet{Focanti2013} study the causes of tax reform in Latin America starting in the 1980s and 1990, respectively. Similarly, \citet[]{Ross2004} studies the relationship between taxation and representation between 1971 and 1997, whereas \citet{Sokoloff2007a} study the evolution of tax institutions comparing the U.S. with Latin America. See also \citet{Sanchez2011} and \citet{Bergman2003}.} However, the \emph{origins} of the Latin American \emph{fiscal} state remain relatively unclear. Additionally, since wars in Latin America have been rare,\footnote{\citet{Centeno:2002qf}.} it is difficult to extend models based on external threats originally developed to understanding the medieval European case.\footnote{\citet{Tilly:1992rr}. See also \citet{Besley2009}.} Importantly, the role of sectoral conflicts within a context of economic structural transformation, taxation and state-building has been overlooked.\footnote{For example, \citet[2]{Schneider:2012rr} argues that even when ``[t]here has been significant attention given to the role of revenues in building early Western European states, and even some attention given to formative moments of state-building in developing countries [but] we have limited insight into what happens when economies change significantly, with new leading sectors, new patterns of social organization, and new requirements of state authorities.''} A few exceptions are \citet[7-8]{Gallo:1991kx} and \citet[8]{Saylor:2014aa} who consider elite conflicts to study state-making and fiscal development in the developing world.\footnote{\citet[]{Wheeler2011} studies how inter-elite cooperation and agreements positively impacted state-making in Europe.} Building on the fiscal sociology paradigm, I propose that the development of the modern fiscal apparatus in Chile was product of sectoral conflicts and compromises that took place around in the 1920's between the industrial and agricultural political elites. The paper presents several panel-data analyses covering almost 100 years of sectoral outputs for a number of Latin American countries in an effort to generalize the theory. Using Cox proportional hazard regressions I model the \emph{contribution} of each sector on the `hazard' of implementing the income tax law. I find that the emergence of the industrial sector \emph{accelerated} the implementation of the income tax while the expansion of the agricultural sector \emph{retarded} or even \emph{precluded} fiscal development. 

