Before estimate the models, it is important to rule out the possibility that income taxation and sectoral development are not linked through a spurious, time-dependent relationship. The occurrence of the outcome of interest (taxation) should not be directly related to time itself, but to the rise of the industrial elite. Within the framework of survival analyses, \autoref{fig:survival:plot} shows the failure rate of the sample average country of implementing the income tax if industrial development had increased/decreased by half (`rapid'/`slow').\footnote{`Failure' in this case means `implementing' the income tax law.} The figure strongly suggests that the implementation of the income tax law is largely accelerated when the size of the industrial sector increases, and that this relationship does not depend directly on time.


