% models
\autoref{results:1} shows 5 models.\footnote{All tables were produced using the  \texttt{texreg} package (\citet[]{Leifeld:2013qr}). All Cox models were computed using the \texttt{survival R}  package (\citet{Therneau:2015zr}). The GEE logistic regression was computed using the \texttt{geepack} package (\citet[]{Hojsgaard:2016}). This paper was written in \LaTeX \; using the dynamic report \texttt{R} package \texttt{knitr} (\citet[]{Xie:2016hl}), for fully replicable research. The simulations were performed using the \texttt{simPH R} package (\citet{Gandrud2015}).} Following \citet{Aidt2009a}, Model 1 computes the lagged conditional hazard ratio of a country which has not yet adopted the income tax adopts it in a given year as a function of industrial and agricultural outputs.\footnote{I do not combine both variables nor do I construct an index. Since I am interested in the \emph{contribution} of each individual sector in the acceleration of the implementation of the income tax law (keeping constant the other), keeping both variables separately is a better strategy. See \autoref{fig:simulation:plots}.} Countries drop out of the sample when they adopt the income tax. Model 2 is also a Cox regression, but with lagged logged variables. By including time-transformed variables, in the form of a lagged dependent variable (to account for partial adjustment of behavior)\footnote{\citet{Wawro2002}.} or ``the use of the natural log transformation [to capture] different forms (or ``shapes'') of the baseline hazard,''\footnote{\citet[75]{Box-Steffensmeier2004}.} Models 1 and 2 are especially well-equipped to account for possible time dependency. Model 3 shows the estimated coefficients of a generalized estimating equation (GEE). Generalized estimating equations were introduced by \citet{Liang1986} to fit clustered, repeated/correlated and panel data.\footnote{\citet[322]{Zorn2006}.} This method is eespecially well suited when the data are binary.\footnote{\citet{Hanley2003a}.} GEE methods require analysts to parameterize the working correlation matrix. Though \citet[ 139]{Hedeker2006} explain that ``the GEE is robust to misspecification of the correlation structure,''\footnote{\citet[ 402]{Carlin2001} argue that ``[r]elatively minor differences in estimates may arise depending on how the estimating equations are weighted, in particular within the generalized estimating equation (GEE) framework.'' \citet{Westgate2016} and \citet[ 227]{Gardiner2009} make the same point.} \citet[338]{Zorn2006} explains that whereas the choice of estimator makes little or no difference, the unit on which the data are grouped makes a big difference. Hence, following the advice of \citet[166]{Hardin2013}, who point out that when ``the observations are clustered (not collected over time) [...] the exchangeable correlation structure'' should be used, I assume an ``independence'' working covariance structure, which corrects for small-sized panel designs.\footnote{\citet[166]{Hardin2013} explains that if ``the number of panels is small, then the independence model may be the best; but [analysts should] calculate the sandwich estimate of variance for use with hypothesis tests and interpretation of coefficient,'' which is what I report in \autoref{results:1}.} From a substantive standpoint, GEE models provide an estimated marginal mean, or the \emph{weighted average} of all cluster-specific effects (or conditional means). Model 4 is a conditional logit  (or ``fixed effects'' model). One important advantage of this strategy is the ability to account for country-specific effects. For example, fiscal development could be a function of country-specific prior state-building capacities.\footnote{I thank Matthias vom Hau for this suggestion.} A number of scholars rightly argue that post-colonial state capacities are in part a function of pre-colonial state-capacities.\footnote{\citet[10]{Wimmer2015a}, \citet{Mahoney:2010aa} and \citet[1426]{Lange2006}.} Fixed-effects should be able to account for this and other unobserved or hard-to-measure covariates, which if left unaccounted for, would introduce omitted variable biases.\footnote{\citet{Angrist:2008fk}.} Model 5 accounts for possible spatial-temporal dependence.\footnote{I thank both Christopher Zorn and David Darmofal for this suggestion.} Given that most of the countries I am modeling are contiguous neighbors, it is reasonable to expect a ``domino'' effect. Theoretically, being the first country in implementing the income tax might not require the same level of domestic effort than being the last one. Early-implementers might not have prior experience, being harder for them to pass the law. To account for this possible spatial-temporal dependence, a cumulative count of countries which have implemented the law at time $t$ was included.\footnote{I clustered the standard errors at the counting variable level. Clustering by the counting variable allows me to cluster by early or late implementers.} 

All in all, the models suggest that the rise of a strong industrial sector largely accelerated the implementation of the income tax law. Moreover, a strong agricultural sector not only has zero impact on fiscal development, but a negative one (models 1, 3 and 4). Both pooled results in model 3 and model 4 give the same results. Importantly, model 4 accounts for country-specific non-measured sources of variation, such as country-specific prior levels of state and fiscal capacities, cultural and geographic differences, among others. I do not find that there was spatial-temporal dependence (model 5).


